{"parse":{"title":"Academy of Foreign Intelligence","pageid":56201474,"revid":826377923,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span id=\"coordinates\"><a href=\"/wiki/Geographic_coordinate_system\" title=\"Geographic coordinate system\">Coordinates</a>: <span class=\"plainlinks nourlexpansion\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?pagename=Academy_of_Foreign_Intelligence&amp;params=55_54_33.9_N_37_37_10.0_E_\"><span class=\"geo-default\"><span class=\"geo-dms\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\"><span class=\"latitude\">55\u00b054\u203233.9\u2033N</span> <span class=\"longitude\">37\u00b037\u203210.0\u2033E</span></span></span><span class=\"geo-multi-punct\">&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;</span><span class=\"geo-nondefault\"><span class=\"geo-dec\" title=\"Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location\">55.909417\u00b0N 37.619444\u00b0E</span><span style=\"display:none\">&#xfeff; / <span class=\"geo\">55.909417; 37.619444</span></span></span></a></span></span></span>\n</p><p>The <b>Academy of Foreign Intelligence</b> (alternatively known as the <b>SVR Academy</b>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> previously known as the <b>Yuri  Andropov Red Banner Institute</b> and the <b>Red Banner Institute</b>)<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ebon1994_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ebon1994-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> is one of the primary <a href=\"/wiki/Espionage\" title=\"Espionage\">espionage</a> academies of <a href=\"/wiki/Russia\" title=\"Russia\">Russia</a>, and previously the <a href=\"/wiki/Soviet_Union\" title=\"Soviet Union\">Soviet Union</a>, serving the <a href=\"/wiki/KGB\" title=\"KGB\">KGB</a> and its successor organization, the <a href=\"/wiki/Foreign_Intelligence_Service_(Russia)\" title=\"Foreign Intelligence Service (Russia)\">Foreign Intelligence Service</a>. It was attended by future <a href=\"/wiki/President_of_Russia\" title=\"President of Russia\">President</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Vladimir_Putin\" title=\"Vladimir Putin\">Vladimir Putin</a> during the 1980s.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Hutchins2012_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hutchins2012-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Jack2005_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Jack2005-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-PutinGevorkyan2000_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PutinGevorkyan2000-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Location\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Location</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Foreign_students\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Foreign students</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Notable_alumni\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notable alumni</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Notable_staff\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notable staff</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Location\">Location</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Academy_of_Foreign_Intelligence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Location\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The school is located near <a href=\"/wiki/Moscow\" title=\"Moscow\">Moscow</a>, with a main facility north of Chelebityevo and a secondary facility at Yurlovo.<sup id=\"cite_ref-West2007_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-West2007-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Truscott2005_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Truscott2005-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Academy_of_Foreign_Intelligence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>An earlier iteration of the school was founded in 1938 and first called the <b>Special Purpose School</b> (<i>Shkola osovogo naznacheniya</i>).<sup id=\"cite_ref-Pringle2015_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Pringle2015-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> It was renamed the Higher Intelligence School (<i>VRSh</i>) from 1948-1968.<sup id=\"cite_ref-FAS_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FAS-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Haslam2015_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Haslam2015-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> It was alternatively known as School 1010 or the 101st School, and referred to as <b>K1</b> or <i>Gridnevka</i> by students.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Pringle2015_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Pringle2015-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-West2007_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-West2007-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Following the <a href=\"/wiki/Dissolution_of_the_Soviet_Union\" title=\"Dissolution of the Soviet Union\">dissolution of the Soviet Union</a>, student enrollment dropped from approximately 300 to around 50.<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-West2007_6-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-West2007-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Foreign_students\">Foreign students</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Academy_of_Foreign_Intelligence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Foreign students\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The Institute trained <a href=\"/wiki/Libyan\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Libyan\">Libyan</a> intelligence officers for <a href=\"/wiki/Muammar_Gaddafi\" title=\"Muammar Gaddafi\">Muammar Gaddafi</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Wills2004_13-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Wills2004-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notable_alumni\">Notable alumni</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Academy_of_Foreign_Intelligence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Notable alumni\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Vladimir_Putin\" title=\"Vladimir Putin\">Vladimir Putin</a></li></ul>\n<p><sup id=\"cite_ref-biography_14-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-biography-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notable_staff\">Notable staff</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Academy_of_Foreign_Intelligence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Notable staff\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Anatoli_Yatskov\" title=\"Anatoli Yatskov\">Anatoli Yatskov</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-Haynes2000_15-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Haynes2000-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Oleg_Nechiporenko\" title=\"Oleg Nechiporenko\">Oleg Nechiporenko</a> (1985 - 1991)<sup id=\"cite_ref-Nechiporenko1993_16-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Nechiporenko1993-16\">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-TrahairMiller2013_17-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-TrahairMiller2013-17\">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Academy_of_Foreign_Intelligence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Weiss, Michael (December 27, 2017). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-kgb-papers-how-putin-learned-his-spycraft-part-1?ref=home\">\"Revealed: The Secret KGB Manual for Recruiting Spies\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Daily_Beast\" title=\"The Daily Beast\">The Daily Beast</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">January 2,</span> 2018</span>. <q>The foreign arm is today known as the SVR, which is the actual successor of the First Chief Directorate; the Andropov Red Banner Institute, in fact, is now called the SVR Academy.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Revealed%3A+The+Secret+KGB+Manual+for+Recruiting+Spies&amp;rft.date=2017-12-27&amp;rft.aulast=Weiss&amp;rft.aufirst=Michael&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thedailybeast.com%2Fthe-kgb-papers-how-putin-learned-his-spycraft-part-1%3Fref%3Dhome&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Ebon1994-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Ebon1994_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Martin Ebon (1994). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=kqcM5V3NXVoC&amp;pg=PA185\"><i>KGB: Death and Rebirth</i></a>. Greenwood Publishing Group. p.&#160;185. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-275-94633-3\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-275-94633-3\">978-0-275-94633-3</a>. <q>More specialized espionage instructions were provided by the Red Banner Institute, renamed in memory of former KGB chief Yuri Andropov and usually simply called the Andropov Institute.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=KGB%3A+Death+and+Rebirth&amp;rft.pages=185&amp;rft.pub=Greenwood+Publishing+Group&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-275-94633-3&amp;rft.au=Martin+Ebon&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DkqcM5V3NXVoC%26pg%3DPA185&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Hutchins2012-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Hutchins2012_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Chris Hutchins (2012). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=4kqWFqR0MPwC&amp;pg=PA40\"><i>Putin</i></a>. Troubador Publishing Ltd. p.&#160;40. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-78088-114-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-78088-114-0\">978-1-78088-114-0</a>. <q>But these were the honeymoon days and she was already expecting their first child when he was sent to Moscow for further training at the Yuri Andropov Red Banner Institute in September 1984 [...] At Red Banner students were given a nom de guerre beginning with the same letter as their surname. Thus Comrade Putin became Comrade Platov.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Putin&amp;rft.pages=40&amp;rft.pub=Troubador+Publishing+Ltd&amp;rft.date=2012&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-78088-114-0&amp;rft.au=Chris+Hutchins&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D4kqWFqR0MPwC%26pg%3DPA40&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Jack2005-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Jack2005_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Andrew Jack (15 December 2005). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=OPdcCAAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PT66\"><i>Inside Putin's Russia: Can There Be Reform without Democracy?</i></a>. Oxford University Press. p.&#160;66. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-19-029336-9\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-19-029336-9\">978-0-19-029336-9</a>. <q>He returned to work in Leningrad's First Department for intelligence for four and a half years, and then attended the elite Andropov Red Banner Institute for intelligence training before his posting to the German Democratic Republic in 1985.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Inside+Putin%27s+Russia%3A+Can+There+Be+Reform+without+Democracy%3F&amp;rft.pages=66&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2005-12-15&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-029336-9&amp;rft.au=Andrew+Jack&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DOPdcCAAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPT66&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-PutinGevorkyan2000-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-PutinGevorkyan2000_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Vladimir Putin; Nataliya Gevorkyan; Natalya Timakova; Andrei Kolesnikov (5 May 2000). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=gcDv5Qww_2AC&amp;pg=PA53\"><i>First Person: An Astonishingly Frank Self-Portrait by Russia's President Vladimir Putin</i></a>. PublicAffairs. p.&#160;53. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7867-2327-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-7867-2327-0\">978-0-7867-2327-0</a>. <q>I worked there for about four and a half years, and then I went to Moscow for training at the Andropov Red Banner Institute, which is now the Academy of Foreign Intelligence.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=First+Person%3A+An+Astonishingly+Frank+Self-Portrait+by+Russia%27s+President+Vladimir+Putin&amp;rft.pages=53&amp;rft.pub=PublicAffairs&amp;rft.date=2000-05-05&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7867-2327-0&amp;rft.au=Vladimir+Putin&amp;rft.au=Nataliya+Gevorkyan&amp;rft.au=Natalya+Timakova&amp;rft.au=Andrei+Kolesnikov&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DgcDv5Qww_2AC%26pg%3DPA53&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-West2007-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-West2007_6-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-West2007_6-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-West2007_6-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Nigel West (26 January 2007). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=0eAHTaMMP6QC&amp;pg=PA10\"><i>Historical Dictionary of Cold War Counterintelligence</i></a>. Scarecrow Press. pp.&#160;10\u201311. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8108-6463-4\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-8108-6463-4\">978-0-8108-6463-4</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Historical+Dictionary+of+Cold+War+Counterintelligence&amp;rft.pages=10-11&amp;rft.pub=Scarecrow+Press&amp;rft.date=2007-01-26&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8108-6463-4&amp;rft.au=Nigel+West&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D0eAHTaMMP6QC%26pg%3DPA10&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Truscott2005-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Truscott2005_7-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Peter Truscott (2005). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=2jzf8FsShUgC\"><i>Putin's Progress: A Biography of Russia's Enigmatic President, Vladimir Putin</i></a>. Pocket Books. p.&#160;46. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7434-9607-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-7434-9607-0\">978-0-7434-9607-0</a>. <q>Four and a half years after joining the KGB's First Department in Leningrad, Putin was sent to Moscow for further training at the Andropov Red Banner Institute, which became the Academy of Foreign Intelligence. This was the KGB's elite school for foreign agents, where the USSR's top spies were trained. Located in woods outside Moscow, the Red Banner Institute is isolated and fenced-off with barbed wire.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Putin%27s+Progress%3A+A+Biography+of+Russia%27s+Enigmatic+President%2C+Vladimir+Putin&amp;rft.pages=46&amp;rft.pub=Pocket+Books&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7434-9607-0&amp;rft.au=Peter+Truscott&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D2jzf8FsShUgC&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Pringle2015-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Pringle2015_8-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Pringle2015_8-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Robert W. Pringle (29 July 2015). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=J9RQCgAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA24\"><i>Historical Dictionary of Russian and Soviet Intelligence</i></a>. Rowman &amp; Littlefield Publishers. p.&#160;24. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-4422-5318-6\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-4422-5318-6\">978-1-4422-5318-6</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Historical+Dictionary+of+Russian+and+Soviet+Intelligence&amp;rft.pages=24&amp;rft.pub=Rowman+%26+Littlefield+Publishers&amp;rft.date=2015-07-29&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-4422-5318-6&amp;rft.au=Robert+W.+Pringle&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DJ9RQCgAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPA24&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-FAS-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-FAS_9-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://fas.org/irp/world/russia/fbis/ForeignIntelligenceService.html#AcademyofForeignIntelligence\">\"Foreign Intelligence Service\"</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Federation_of_American_Scientists\" title=\"Federation of American Scientists\">Federation of American Scientists</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">January 2,</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Foreign+Intelligence+Service&amp;rft.pub=Federation+of+American+Scientists&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Ffas.org%2Firp%2Fworld%2Frussia%2Ffbis%2FForeignIntelligenceService.html%23AcademyofForeignIntelligence&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Haslam2015-10\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Haslam2015_10-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Jonathan Haslam (24 September 2015). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=tLOYCgAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PT317\"><i>Near and Distant Neighbours: A New History of Soviet Intelligence</i></a>. OUP Oxford. p.&#160;317. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-19-101812-1\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-19-101812-1\">978-0-19-101812-1</a>. <q>From 1943 it was called the Intelligence School (RaSh), then, from September 1948, the Higher Intelligence School (VRSh), also known as School 101.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Near+and+Distant+Neighbours%3A+A+New+History+of+Soviet+Intelligence&amp;rft.pages=317&amp;rft.pub=OUP+Oxford&amp;rft.date=2015-09-24&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-101812-1&amp;rft.au=Jonathan+Haslam&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DtLOYCgAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPT317&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-11\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-11\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=VtcVAQAAMAAJ\"><i>FBIS Daily Report: Central Eurasia</i></a>. The Service. 1995. p.&#160;3. <q>After the war V.V. Gridnev served as director of the 101st School, which trained personnel for our foreign intelligence service. The future intelligence agents idolized their director and informally called the 101st School \u201cGridnevka.\u201d Later it became the higher training establishment of our intelligence service\u2014the Yu.V. Andropov Red Banner Institute, was created on the basis of that school.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=FBIS+Daily+Report%3A+Central+Eurasia&amp;rft.pages=3&amp;rft.pub=The+Service&amp;rft.date=1995&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DVtcVAQAAMAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-12\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-12\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=mAK6AAAAIAAJ\"><i>Asia-Pacific Defence Reporter</i></a>. Peter Isaacson. 1993. p.&#160;27. <q>The number of students at the Andropov Red Banner Institute, which trains intelligence staff, has dropped from 300 to about 50.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Asia-Pacific+Defence+Reporter&amp;rft.pages=27&amp;rft.pub=Peter+Isaacson&amp;rft.date=1993&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DmAK6AAAAIAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Wills2004-13\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Wills2004_13-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">David C. Wills (26 October 2004). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=0ckzAAAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA168\"><i>The First War on Terrorism: Counter-terrorism Policy during the Reagan Administration</i></a>. Rowman &amp; Littlefield Publishers. p.&#160;168. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-4175-0361-2\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-4175-0361-2\">978-1-4175-0361-2</a>. <q>Additional intelligence showed that the KGB had trained Libyan intelligence officers at the Andropov Institute in Moscow, and regularly supplied Qaddafi with reports on American naval maneuvers in the Mediterranean.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+First+War+on+Terrorism%3A+Counter-terrorism+Policy+during+the+Reagan+Administration&amp;rft.pages=168&amp;rft.pub=Rowman+%26+Littlefield+Publishers&amp;rft.date=2004-10-26&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-4175-0361-2&amp;rft.au=David+C.+Wills&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D0ckzAAAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPA168&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-biography-14\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-biography_14-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20141025134424/http://www.nalyvaichenko.org/UserFiles/File/chesno.pdf\">Biographic information</a> submitted to the <a href=\"/wiki/Central_Election_Commission_of_Ukraine\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Central Election Commission of Ukraine\">Central Election Commission of Ukraine</a> on 1 August 2012</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Haynes2000-15\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Haynes2000_15-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">John Earl Haynes (August 2000). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=M8p00bTFvRkC&amp;pg=PA393\"><i>Venona: Decoding Soviet Espionage in America</i></a>. Yale University Press. p.&#160;393. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-300-12987-8\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-300-12987-8\">978-0-300-12987-8</a>. <q>After the war he undertook numerous intelligence assignments and headed one of the schools of the KGB's Andropov Red Banner Institute for training of KGB personnel.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Venona%3A+Decoding+Soviet+Espionage+in+America&amp;rft.pages=393&amp;rft.pub=Yale+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2000-08&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-300-12987-8&amp;rft.au=John+Earl+Haynes&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DM8p00bTFvRkC%26pg%3DPA393&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Nechiporenko1993-16\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Nechiporenko1993_16-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a href=\"/wiki/Oleg_Nechiporenko\" title=\"Oleg Nechiporenko\">Oleg Nechiporenko</a> (1993). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=6jJ3AAAAMAAJ\"><i>Passport to Assassination: The Never-before-told Story of Lee Harvey Oswald by the KGB Colonel who Knew Him</i></a>. Carol Publishing Group. p.&#160;339. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-55972-210-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-55972-210-0\">978-1-55972-210-0</a>. <q>Nechiporenko remained in Mexico until 1965 and returned again in 1967. From 1971 until 1985 he was dispatched on numerous special missions for the KGB throughout South and Central America and North Vietnam. From 1985 he taught at the Soviet Intelligence officer's college, the Andropov Institute. He retired with distinction in 1991.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Passport+to+Assassination%3A+The+Never-before-told+Story+of+Lee+Harvey+Oswald+by+the+KGB+Colonel+who+Knew+Him&amp;rft.pages=339&amp;rft.pub=Carol+Publishing+Group&amp;rft.date=1993&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-55972-210-0&amp;rft.au=Oleg+Nechiporenko&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D6jJ3AAAAMAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-TrahairMiller2013-17\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-TrahairMiller2013_17-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">R. C. S. Trahair; Robert L. Miller (18 October 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=g3LtFS3rl9MC&amp;pg=PA258\"><i>Encyclopedia of Cold War Espionage, Spies, and Secret Operations</i></a>. Enigma Books. p.&#160;258. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-936274-25-3\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-936274-25-3\">978-1-936274-25-3</a>. <q>Until 1985 Nechiporenko served the Soviets in Central America and North Vietnam, and taught at Moscow's Andropov Institute.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Encyclopedia+of+Cold+War+Espionage%2C+Spies%2C+and+Secret+Operations&amp;rft.pages=258&amp;rft.pub=Enigma+Books&amp;rft.date=2013-10-18&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-936274-25-3&amp;rft.au=R.+C.+S.+Trahair&amp;rft.au=Robert+L.+Miller&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dg3LtFS3rl9MC%26pg%3DPA258&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAcademy+of+Foreign+Intelligence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1319\nCached time: 20180908021127\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.212 seconds\nReal tim